# Task29: Chronicon Boundary Discovery

## Objective

Review the current codebase and documentation to determine whether any existing classes, tests, packages, or concepts already belong to `codex-chronicon`.

This is primarily a discovery and boundary-definition task.

Do not implement audit yet.

Do not move domain events.

Do not move event infrastructure.

Do not move canonical lifecycle services.

The goal is to clarify what belongs to Chronicon before creating audit/history/timeline functionality.

## Decision Context

`codex-chronicon` represents the memory of the manuscript.

It should own audit/history/timeline projections derived from domain events.

However, Codex already has:

- domain events
- actors
- timestamps
- event dispatchers
- event subscribers
- lifecycle services
- content type/item/revision state

Not all of these belong to Chronicon.

Important distinction:

```text
codex-codex
  emits domain events

codex-chronicon
  listens to domain events
  records audit/history/timeline projections
 ```

 Domain events are canonical facts and should stay in codex-codex.

 Generic event infrastructure should stay in codex-fundamentum.

 Chronicon should not own the canonical lifecycle.

